WEBVTT

00:00:00.320 --> 00:00:04.240
So as we get started here, I just want to have you look at this big wall of text.

00:00:04.240 --> 00:00:08.640
Now this is just hard to read. That's the main thing I want you to get out of this.

00:00:08.640 --> 00:00:11.600
Particularly when compared to this on the right.

00:00:12.480 --> 00:00:18.080
Now over here we've got great use of indentation, whitespace, formatting, style.

00:00:18.080 --> 00:00:20.639
It just looks more pleasurable to read.

00:00:21.680 --> 00:00:25.840
And this concept doesn't just apply to prose. It also applies to code.

00:00:26.719 --> 00:00:29.440
For example, I'm sure we've all seen code like this.

00:00:30.240 --> 00:00:32.880
This is a big for loop. It's very compressed.

00:00:32.880 --> 00:00:35.360
If I were to ask you what this does very quickly,

00:00:35.360 --> 00:00:39.119
it would take you a couple seconds to kind of figure out what it's doing.

00:00:39.119 --> 00:00:39.759
Maybe longer.

00:00:40.720 --> 00:00:42.400
Compare that to this.

00:00:42.400 --> 00:00:46.320
This is a formatted for loop, which is the exact same content.

00:00:46.320 --> 00:00:51.200
But it's much easier to see that all this does is print out even or odd based on the number.

00:00:53.279 --> 00:00:56.000
I think we can all agree that this looks better.

00:00:56.560 --> 00:01:00.160
The problem is that just getting to this form is sometimes really tedious.

00:01:01.040 --> 00:01:04.559
For example, here I have a pipe chain.

00:01:04.559 --> 00:01:07.519
This pipe chain extends off the right hand side of the screen.

00:01:08.879 --> 00:01:10.800
Watch me struggle to format this thing.

00:01:11.760 --> 00:01:13.839
I might first work on aligning the pipes.

00:01:14.959 --> 00:01:19.839
And then I might decide, well actually I want this pivot longer call to be expanded as well.

00:01:19.839 --> 00:01:21.839
So I spend some time doing that too.

00:01:22.239 --> 00:01:25.599
And again, I think we can all agree that this looks better.

00:01:25.599 --> 00:01:31.599
But at the end of a long workday, I'm going to start doing this manual work less and less.

00:01:32.959 --> 00:01:33.760
So let's reset.

00:01:35.680 --> 00:01:41.279
Wouldn't it be cool if there was a tool where you could snap your fingers

00:01:42.320 --> 00:01:43.519
and the pipes would realign?

00:01:45.440 --> 00:01:50.239
Or maybe you could snap your fingers again

00:01:50.480 --> 00:01:53.680
and it would expand your pivot longer call automatically.

00:01:55.199 --> 00:01:59.360
If that sounds interesting to you, then you will be very interested in AIR.

00:02:00.400 --> 00:02:04.320
AIR is an extremely fast R code formatter.

00:02:04.879 --> 00:02:09.600
If you've never heard of a formatter before, it takes messy code and turns it into pretty code,

00:02:09.600 --> 00:02:11.360
just like you saw on the previous slide.

00:02:12.160 --> 00:02:16.800
And when hooked up to your editor, AIR gives you a number of formatting superpowers,

00:02:16.800 --> 00:02:18.800
which we'll be looking at in this talk.

00:02:20.720 --> 00:02:22.479
Now, if you're thinking to yourself, like,

00:02:23.279 --> 00:02:25.600
is this just like one more tool that I have to learn?

00:02:25.600 --> 00:02:28.639
Is this a lot of things for me to have to set up in my project?

00:02:29.279 --> 00:02:33.839
Know that we have made setting up AIR in an existing project as easy as possible.

00:02:34.720 --> 00:02:36.000
It's actually only two steps.

00:02:36.800 --> 00:02:40.399
You add some configuration that tells your IDE how to use AIR,

00:02:41.039 --> 00:02:42.960
and then you format all of your files.

00:02:43.839 --> 00:02:47.119
In fact, it's so easy, we're just going to go ahead and show you how it works.

00:02:47.119 --> 00:02:49.039
We're going to jump over into Positron here.

00:02:49.119 --> 00:02:53.919
And what you need to know about Positron is that it already comes bundled with AIR.

00:02:53.919 --> 00:02:56.960
There's actually nothing else you need to do to install it.

00:02:56.960 --> 00:02:58.639
You may have it, and you didn't even know.

00:03:00.080 --> 00:03:02.080
So we're going to do two things in this project.

00:03:02.080 --> 00:03:03.679
There's three R files here.

00:03:03.679 --> 00:03:05.839
We're going to add that configuration we talked about,

00:03:05.839 --> 00:03:07.839
and then we're going to format these three R files.

00:03:08.639 --> 00:03:14.080
To add the configuration, all we do is run this command, initialize workspace folder.

00:03:14.080 --> 00:03:17.919
And over here, you can see a couple of configuration files have been added.

00:03:18.479 --> 00:03:22.479
All these do is tell Positron to use AIR to format your file.

00:03:23.440 --> 00:03:24.479
Go ahead and commit those.

00:03:30.240 --> 00:03:34.000
The next step is to actually format these files using AIR.

00:03:34.000 --> 00:03:36.240
You see that button in the bottom right-hand corner?

00:03:37.039 --> 00:03:38.880
Click to format the workspace folder.

00:03:38.880 --> 00:03:40.639
Click to format the workspace folder.

00:03:41.759 --> 00:03:47.119
If we click that, then magically, all of our files have now been formatted with AIR.

00:03:48.479 --> 00:03:52.000
If you use Git, this is a great chance to kind of look and see

00:03:52.000 --> 00:03:55.600
what AIR has done in terms of, like, remote formatting the code to make it pretty.

00:03:57.039 --> 00:04:00.000
But if you don't care, you can just commit and say,

00:04:00.000 --> 00:04:01.919
OK, looks good, formatted all the files.

00:04:03.919 --> 00:04:07.360
So that's all it takes to actually get set up to use AIR.

00:04:08.080 --> 00:04:09.199
But that's not the fun part.

00:04:09.919 --> 00:04:12.639
The fun part is using AIR on a day-to-day basis.

00:04:13.199 --> 00:04:15.199
And again, if you're thinking, is this one of those tools

00:04:15.199 --> 00:04:17.440
where I have to learn a whole bunch to use this thing?

00:04:18.160 --> 00:04:21.359
Well, actually, we believe that if you know how to save a file,

00:04:21.920 --> 00:04:23.519
you already know how to use AIR.

00:04:24.399 --> 00:04:25.440
We're going to look at that next.

00:04:26.799 --> 00:04:31.760
We'll jump over into a file here called visualize.r, another file in our project.

00:04:31.760 --> 00:04:35.839
We've got some ggplot2 code that's incomplete, so we'll go ahead and finish it out.

00:04:36.799 --> 00:04:40.320
Plus geoblind, maybe, and theme minimal.

00:04:41.359 --> 00:04:45.440
And the key here is that as I'm just trying to get this out of my head,

00:04:45.440 --> 00:04:47.359
I don't really care what the code looks like.

00:04:47.359 --> 00:04:49.040
That's not what I'm thinking about at the time.

00:04:49.920 --> 00:04:51.920
But now that I have gotten it out of my head,

00:04:52.799 --> 00:04:55.760
I take a breath, and I save the file,

00:04:56.399 --> 00:05:00.720
and AIR kicks in, and it reflows your pipes automatically.

00:05:00.959 --> 00:05:04.559
Or maybe I decide, well, actually, I'm not ready to do my plots yet.

00:05:04.559 --> 00:05:06.399
I need a couple extra columns.

00:05:06.399 --> 00:05:10.079
So I might do this mutate call and add a few extra columns on.

00:05:12.640 --> 00:05:16.480
And again, as I'm typing this, I'm not really thinking about what the code looks like.

00:05:16.480 --> 00:05:20.559
I just am trying to get this out of my head so that it's on the screen here.

00:05:21.279 --> 00:05:27.679
But now that I have, I take a breath, and I save, and AIR kicks in again,

00:05:28.160 --> 00:05:32.399
and AIR kicks in again, reflowing the pipe, reflowing the mutate call,

00:05:32.399 --> 00:05:36.000
adding whitespace, generally making things look pretty automatically.

00:05:38.239 --> 00:05:40.799
You might hear that I'm saying I'm doing this on save,

00:05:40.799 --> 00:05:43.200
and, you know, I save hundreds of times a day.

00:05:43.200 --> 00:05:46.160
So you might be wondering, is this going to slow you down at all?

00:05:46.799 --> 00:05:48.000
You know, you save a lot.

00:05:49.279 --> 00:05:54.239
One of our goals with AIR is to be imperceptible with format on save.

00:05:54.239 --> 00:05:58.000
It should be so fast that you question if it even ran.

00:05:59.519 --> 00:06:03.760
To put some concrete numbers behind this, we'll look at dplyr's across.r.

00:06:03.760 --> 00:06:06.720
This is a big thousand-line R file, so pretty big.

00:06:07.679 --> 00:06:11.839
It takes AIR around 20 milliseconds to format this file.

00:06:12.640 --> 00:06:17.200
To put that in perspective, if you blink, it takes about 200 milliseconds.

00:06:17.839 --> 00:06:19.040
So it's extremely fast.

00:06:20.000 --> 00:06:26.000
If we were to scale up, all of dplyr has about 150 R files in it.

00:06:26.640 --> 00:06:30.239
If you were to format the whole project, it takes 200 milliseconds.

00:06:31.119 --> 00:06:35.279
You can format all of dplyr in the blink of an eye.

00:06:37.839 --> 00:06:40.480
Now, if you're on the border of deciding, you know,

00:06:40.480 --> 00:06:42.559
should I use AIR or should I not in my project,

00:06:43.119 --> 00:06:46.239
know that if you do, you will be in good company.

00:06:47.119 --> 00:06:51.679
Pretty much all of the packages in RLib and the tidyverse at this point use AIR.

00:06:51.679 --> 00:06:55.359
We've run it over hundreds of thousands of lines of R code at this point,

00:06:55.359 --> 00:06:56.799
and we feel very good about it.

00:06:57.359 --> 00:07:01.359
In fact, just this morning, I removed the beta label from AIR.

00:07:01.359 --> 00:07:05.279
So if that's been holding you back, you should feel free to use it at this time.

00:07:08.959 --> 00:07:13.279
So our goal with the formatter is that once you start using it,

00:07:13.279 --> 00:07:16.640
it will be hard for you to go back to your formatter-less lifestyle.

00:07:18.239 --> 00:07:21.279
And that's something we've certainly managed to achieve with Hadley,

00:07:21.279 --> 00:07:25.279
because now when he saves a file and he does a new format, it feels broken for him.

00:07:26.160 --> 00:07:28.799
And we kind of knew that Hadley would be an easy win for us

00:07:28.799 --> 00:07:31.359
because he has always cared a lot about style.

00:07:32.320 --> 00:07:35.440
But now I would like to talk a little bit about what happens

00:07:35.440 --> 00:07:38.959
when you have a room full of programmers who all care a lot about style.

00:07:40.480 --> 00:07:41.760
Something like this happens.

00:07:43.359 --> 00:07:46.239
So these are excerpts from our GitHub organization

00:07:47.119 --> 00:07:49.600
where a pull request came in,

00:07:49.600 --> 00:07:53.279
and the reviewer is focusing part of the review

00:07:53.279 --> 00:07:55.440
on the style of the code rather than on the contents.

00:07:56.559 --> 00:08:00.320
So that's not a good place to be in, and we call this collaborative friction.

00:08:02.399 --> 00:08:05.040
And the nice thing about the formatter workflow

00:08:05.040 --> 00:08:09.279
is that if everyone on your team gets on the same page

00:08:09.279 --> 00:08:11.839
and is using the formatter as configured in a project,

00:08:12.799 --> 00:08:15.839
and the formatter kicks in every time a file is saved,

00:08:16.640 --> 00:08:19.600
well, the code is never going to go out of sync

00:08:19.600 --> 00:08:22.480
with the expectations around the style.

00:08:23.359 --> 00:08:25.839
And so that fully solves the problem of collaborative friction

00:08:25.839 --> 00:08:26.959
that we saw in the last slide.

00:08:28.799 --> 00:08:32.400
So you might think, but what about an external contributor?

00:08:32.960 --> 00:08:35.200
They might not be using the formatter.

00:08:36.640 --> 00:08:39.280
Well, for this scenario, we have a GitHub action

00:08:39.280 --> 00:08:41.119
that you can set up in your repository.

00:08:41.840 --> 00:08:45.200
And when you do, a robot will come in for every contribution

00:08:45.200 --> 00:08:46.400
and check the style for you.

00:08:47.200 --> 00:08:51.599
And it will even suggest fixes when something is not right,

00:08:52.640 --> 00:08:56.159
and the contributor can merge the fixes by themselves.

00:08:56.719 --> 00:08:59.679
And so there's no human in the loop anymore for checking the style.

00:09:00.880 --> 00:09:03.840
And so hopefully, when the reviewer comes in,

00:09:03.840 --> 00:09:06.320
they can focus on the contents of the code

00:09:06.320 --> 00:09:08.400
and get the contribution much faster.

00:09:08.880 --> 00:09:12.640
So now there's another aspect to collaborative friction,

00:09:12.640 --> 00:09:14.640
and that has to do with configuration.

00:09:17.200 --> 00:09:20.159
And to see this, here's an example of a configuration file

00:09:20.159 --> 00:09:22.479
for a formatter called clang-format.

00:09:24.000 --> 00:09:25.679
And that's for C code.

00:09:25.679 --> 00:09:28.400
And as you can see, it has a lot of options,

00:09:28.400 --> 00:09:29.440
extremely configurable.

00:09:31.599 --> 00:09:34.080
And that's only a small sample of the option

00:09:34.080 --> 00:09:37.039
that you can set to specify how you want your code to look.

00:09:38.719 --> 00:09:41.280
And that's how you want your code to be formatted.

00:09:42.719 --> 00:09:47.200
So when it comes to configure the formatter for a project,

00:09:47.919 --> 00:09:49.119
that's a lot of complexity.

00:09:50.000 --> 00:09:53.760
And maybe some of you would appreciate this flexibility,

00:09:53.760 --> 00:09:56.400
but we would like to argue that there is a hidden cost to it.

00:09:57.679 --> 00:10:00.640
And to see that, let's see an example with Davis and I

00:10:01.440 --> 00:10:03.840
trying to configure a formatter for Rust code,

00:10:03.840 --> 00:10:06.239
because we write a lot of Rust code these days.

00:10:06.239 --> 00:10:08.960
Suggesting that we might be able to use a particular option.

00:10:09.760 --> 00:10:10.960
But then I come in, and I'm like,

00:10:10.960 --> 00:10:13.119
well, actually, I don't like that option.

00:10:13.119 --> 00:10:15.359
I think it's better if the code looks this way.

00:10:15.359 --> 00:10:17.359
And then we're just back here again.

00:10:17.359 --> 00:10:19.119
So we're back to collaborative friction,

00:10:19.119 --> 00:10:22.159
because now we have to agree as a team

00:10:22.159 --> 00:10:24.719
on all the options that we want to use in the project.

00:10:26.479 --> 00:10:28.400
So that's why we made the formatter

00:10:28.400 --> 00:10:29.760
more like a live switch.

00:10:30.479 --> 00:10:32.000
It's either on or off.

00:10:32.640 --> 00:10:34.799
You're either using the formatter with all the rules

00:10:34.799 --> 00:10:36.880
that we have implemented, or you're not.

00:10:38.400 --> 00:10:41.840
And our configuration file looks more like this.

00:10:41.840 --> 00:10:46.239
So you can decide how wide you want your code to be on average.

00:10:46.239 --> 00:10:49.200
And you have a couple of options about indentation.

00:10:49.200 --> 00:10:51.679
So whether you want to use tabs or spaces,

00:10:51.679 --> 00:10:54.640
and how wide an indentation should be.

00:10:56.000 --> 00:10:58.880
So we have kind of a strict formatter.

00:10:58.880 --> 00:11:02.479
But does that mean that you have absolutely no say

00:11:02.479 --> 00:11:04.640
as to how the code is laid out?

00:11:05.039 --> 00:11:05.840
With the formatter.

00:11:07.119 --> 00:11:09.280
Well, not quite, because one of our goals

00:11:09.280 --> 00:11:11.679
was to give you power and control

00:11:11.679 --> 00:11:13.440
over how the code is laid out.

00:11:13.440 --> 00:11:15.599
And this happens in two ways.

00:11:17.280 --> 00:11:19.760
And the first way is persistent line breaks.

00:11:20.320 --> 00:11:23.119
And here we have an example with a couple of expressions,

00:11:23.840 --> 00:11:25.679
a list call and a ggplot pipeline.

00:11:26.239 --> 00:11:29.119
And they are laid out in what we call the flat layout,

00:11:29.119 --> 00:11:30.320
which is like horizontal.

00:11:31.119 --> 00:11:33.039
And let's say that you, as a programmer,

00:11:33.039 --> 00:11:34.799
want to go to the expanded layout,

00:11:34.799 --> 00:11:36.080
which is more vertical.

00:11:37.200 --> 00:11:38.880
The idea of persistent line breaks

00:11:38.880 --> 00:11:40.640
is that you are going to find the first element

00:11:40.640 --> 00:11:44.320
in that expression, insert a line break, save the file.

00:11:44.960 --> 00:11:47.280
And it's going to be taken as the line break

00:11:47.280 --> 00:11:50.400
is an instruction for the formatter to go to expand it.

00:11:50.400 --> 00:11:52.880
So let's see what it looks like.

00:11:52.880 --> 00:11:55.200
With the list call, you can find the first argument,

00:11:55.200 --> 00:11:57.679
insert a line break, you save, goes to expanded.

00:11:59.039 --> 00:12:01.679
And with the ggplot pipeline, you find the first element,

00:12:01.679 --> 00:12:03.919
insert a line break, you save, and it goes to expanded.

00:12:05.119 --> 00:12:07.520
And the nice thing is that this process is reversible,

00:12:07.520 --> 00:12:09.280
so you can remove the line break,

00:12:09.280 --> 00:12:10.880
you save, it goes back to flat.

00:12:12.239 --> 00:12:14.080
And same with the list call.

00:12:15.200 --> 00:12:18.000
So that's one of our favorite features with the formatter

00:12:18.000 --> 00:12:20.000
because it really gives you a grip on your code.

00:12:21.200 --> 00:12:24.400
And we hope that you will like it too.

00:12:26.719 --> 00:12:29.840
So the second way you have control is with magic commands.

00:12:30.640 --> 00:12:32.880
So here we have an example with the igraph package,

00:12:32.880 --> 00:12:35.520
which is a package to work with graphs.

00:12:35.520 --> 00:12:39.200
And it has a domain-specific language to specify graphs

00:12:39.200 --> 00:12:41.359
with plus and minus operators.

00:12:42.320 --> 00:12:45.359
And if you try to use the formatter with this code,

00:12:45.359 --> 00:12:48.799
it's not going to know how to do a good job with this code.

00:12:50.320 --> 00:12:52.880
And you get something that doesn't look like a graph anymore.

00:12:53.840 --> 00:12:55.599
So what you can do in these situations

00:12:55.599 --> 00:12:57.919
is use a magic command with a skip directive.

00:12:58.880 --> 00:13:02.239
And that will instruct to ignore the next expression.

00:13:03.599 --> 00:13:04.799
So if you use igraph,

00:13:05.840 --> 00:13:08.239
you're not going to want to sprinkle your code with magic commands.

00:13:08.239 --> 00:13:11.119
So there's also a way in the configuration file

00:13:11.119 --> 00:13:13.599
to specify which function should be skipped

00:13:13.599 --> 00:13:14.719
across the whole project.

00:13:16.719 --> 00:13:20.640
Now, magic commands are not only for turning off the formatter.

00:13:20.640 --> 00:13:23.039
And we are starting to look into new ways

00:13:23.039 --> 00:13:26.239
to specify how to layout code.

00:13:27.039 --> 00:13:29.520
And one feature that is currently in development

00:13:30.320 --> 00:13:32.080
is a tabular directive.

00:13:33.200 --> 00:13:34.880
And that's going to be extremely useful

00:13:34.880 --> 00:13:36.640
with Tribble calls, for example.

00:13:37.840 --> 00:13:38.640
So if you don't know,

00:13:38.640 --> 00:13:41.679
Tribble is a tidy-verse way of creating a data frame

00:13:42.719 --> 00:13:46.479
where you enter tabular data in your script.

00:13:47.679 --> 00:13:50.479
And historically, it's always been kind of a pain

00:13:50.479 --> 00:13:52.479
to format these Tribble calls

00:13:52.479 --> 00:13:56.000
because you have to manually align all of the columns.

00:13:56.880 --> 00:13:57.919
But with the formatter,

00:14:00.320 --> 00:14:02.159
that becomes automatic.

00:14:02.159 --> 00:14:03.119
You just save the file

00:14:03.119 --> 00:14:05.200
and everything goes in the right place.

00:14:05.919 --> 00:14:08.559
And if you edit one of the fields,

00:14:08.559 --> 00:14:09.679
create some misalignments,

00:14:10.320 --> 00:14:11.599
you only need to save the file

00:14:11.599 --> 00:14:13.039
and everything is perfect

00:14:13.039 --> 00:14:15.039
and you get a nice little Tribble call.

00:14:16.239 --> 00:14:18.400
So that feature is still in development

00:14:18.400 --> 00:14:19.760
but coming soon to the formatter.

00:14:20.799 --> 00:14:21.760
But as you can see,

00:14:21.760 --> 00:14:24.880
even though we have a strict configuration,

00:14:25.440 --> 00:14:27.840
we still give you many ways to control

00:14:28.559 --> 00:14:30.559
how the code should be laid out.

00:14:32.960 --> 00:14:34.320
So in general,

00:14:34.320 --> 00:14:36.559
we think that the formatter will save you time,

00:14:36.559 --> 00:14:38.320
that it will make your code pretty,

00:14:39.039 --> 00:14:41.599
that it will reduce collaborative friction,

00:14:41.599 --> 00:14:42.559
and in general,

00:14:42.559 --> 00:14:45.119
just spark joy in your development workflow.

00:14:47.919 --> 00:14:49.039
So as we wrap up here,

00:14:49.599 --> 00:14:50.719
we actually have one more thing

00:14:50.719 --> 00:14:51.679
that we wanted to show you.

00:14:52.640 --> 00:14:54.159
Now, all the examples and videos

00:14:54.159 --> 00:14:55.280
that you've seen so far

00:14:55.280 --> 00:14:56.799
have been in Positron.

00:14:57.760 --> 00:14:59.440
But the cool thing about Air

00:14:59.440 --> 00:15:01.679
is that it's actually an external tool

00:15:01.679 --> 00:15:02.880
that Positron uses.

00:15:03.840 --> 00:15:05.679
What that means is that

00:15:05.679 --> 00:15:08.159
it can also be used in RStudio.

00:15:09.520 --> 00:15:10.479
And in fact,

00:15:10.479 --> 00:15:13.520
it can be used in any IDE.

00:15:14.719 --> 00:15:18.320
NeoVim, Zed, Helix, VS Code,

00:15:18.320 --> 00:15:20.320
Positron, RStudio.

00:15:20.320 --> 00:15:22.239
Because we use the industry standard

00:15:22.239 --> 00:15:23.679
language server protocol,

00:15:24.159 --> 00:15:26.239
it means that Air can be used anywhere.

00:15:28.559 --> 00:15:31.039
You see, we want Air to be a tool

00:15:31.039 --> 00:15:33.520
for the entire R community.

00:15:33.520 --> 00:15:35.039
And this means providing great support

00:15:35.039 --> 00:15:36.640
for all IDEs,

00:15:36.640 --> 00:15:39.039
not just Positron and RStudio.

00:15:39.919 --> 00:15:41.039
Because at the end of the day,

00:15:41.679 --> 00:15:42.640
Air is for everyone,

00:15:43.200 --> 00:15:44.799
no matter where you write your R code.

00:15:45.440 --> 00:15:46.239
Thank you very much.

00:15:46.799 --> 00:16:00.799
We'll repeat your question.

00:16:10.799 --> 00:16:12.000
Yeah, do you want me to go?

00:16:12.000 --> 00:16:12.239
Yeah.

00:16:13.119 --> 00:16:14.080
So, should we switch away

00:16:14.080 --> 00:16:15.599
from Stylar to Air and why?

00:16:16.239 --> 00:16:16.479
Yes.

00:16:19.280 --> 00:16:20.400
We have talked to Lorenz,

00:16:20.400 --> 00:16:22.479
who is the current maintainer of Stylar.

00:16:22.479 --> 00:16:25.280
He is very happy with where Air is at this point.

00:16:25.280 --> 00:16:28.400
It is over 100 times faster.

00:16:28.400 --> 00:16:30.880
The performance is a feature.

00:16:30.880 --> 00:16:33.359
When you save with Stylar in large files,

00:16:33.359 --> 00:16:36.000
it takes over a second sometimes to save the file.

00:16:36.000 --> 00:16:37.760
When you do that hundreds of times a day,

00:16:37.760 --> 00:16:38.799
it does slow you down.

00:16:39.679 --> 00:16:41.679
We think the performance is a feature

00:16:41.679 --> 00:16:43.440
and we think you should switch.

00:16:44.239 --> 00:16:45.840
And also, in Stylar,

00:16:45.840 --> 00:16:46.960
there is no line splitting,

00:16:47.760 --> 00:16:49.760
like going to the expanded layout.

00:16:49.760 --> 00:16:53.440
So, that's a limitation that the new format solves.

00:16:57.119 --> 00:16:59.359
How did you manage to make Air so fast?

00:17:00.400 --> 00:17:01.679
The one word we haven't said,

00:17:02.239 --> 00:17:02.640
Rust.

00:17:06.719 --> 00:17:07.040
That's it.

00:17:13.439 --> 00:17:14.479
Thank you.

